# ds1302

Bit-banged driver for the **DS1302** Trickle-Charge Timekeeping IC.

## Hardware connection

| DS1302 pin | ESP32-C3 GPIO |
| ---------- | ------------- |
| RST / CE   | GPIO 20       |
| DAT / IO   | GPIO 10       |
| CLK / SCLK | GPIO 9        |
| VCC2       | 3.3 V         |
| GND        | GND           |

A backup coin cell (CR2032) connects between VCC1 and GND to keep time
when main power is off.

## API

```c
// Initialise GPIO lines and start the oscillator if it was stopped.
// Safe to call on every boot — does NOT overwrite time if the oscillator
// was already running (CH bit == 0).
void ds1302_init(int rst_gpio, int dat_gpio, int clk_gpio);

// Read current time from the RTC.  All values are decimal (not BCD).
void ds1302_get_time(uint8_t *hour, uint8_t *minute, uint8_t *second);

// Write new time to the RTC.  Temporarily disables write-protect (WP),
// writes the three registers, then re-enables WP.
void ds1302_set_time(uint8_t hour, uint8_t minute, uint8_t second);
```

## Important notes on power-on safety

RST and CLK are pulled LOW immediately at `ds1302_init()` using
`gpio_config()` before any communication.  This prevents spurious
transactions caused by GPIO floating during the ESP32 boot sequence,
which could corrupt the RTC registers.

Write-protect is re-enabled after every `ds1302_set_time()` call so that
bus noise cannot accidentally overwrite the stored time.
